The IJR has released the findings of the 2015 South African Reconciliation Barometer survey. CAPE TOWN - The Institute for Justice and Reconciliation (IJR) has released the findings of the 2015 South African Reconciliation Barometer survey.It measures public opinion on national unity and reconciliation.The study conducted from August to September 2015, explored South African s access to resources including education, finance and geographical separation, in order to achieve their own personal goals.It found over 43% feel they have access to the financial resources they need. About 2,219 respondent and their responses are weighed to adequately represent the adult population of South Africa, in terms of race, gender and province. (Edited by Zamangwane Shange)